## Day 5 – Users & Groups

### Objective

Understand Linux users, groups, ownership, and directory permissions.

### Activities

- Created Linux groups (developers, finance, interns)
- Created users (alice, bob, charlie)
- Assigned users to groups
- Explored `/etc/passwd` and `/etc/group`
- Used `id` and `groups` to verify memberships
- Investigated directory permissions with `namei -l`

### Biggest Lesson

File permissions alone do not determine access. Every directory in the path must also allow traversal using the execute (`x`) permission.

### Challenge

I received a "Permission denied" error when trying to access `/home/alice/testfile.txt`.

### Root Cause

I did not have execute permission on Alice's home directory, so I could not traverse the path.

### Resolution

Used `namei -l` to identify exactly where access was blocked.

### Commands Practised

- whoami
- id
- groups
- groupadd
- useradd
- usermod
- grep
- ls -ld
- namei

### Reflection

This lesson helped me understand that Linux permissions are checked at every level of a file path. I also learned how users, groups, and ownership work together to implement the Principle of Least Privilege.
